When installing JIRA on Windows or Linux using its default installation package (.exe or .bin), it will only ask what control/HTTP ports it should use (8005 and 8080 by default).

It's possible to change that, but as it turns out, when running the installer on a server with multiple network interfaces that already has this port being used by the localhost (or another) interface, may lead JIRA to a failure on the startup. The ideal scenario is the JIRA installer asking to which port *and* network interface (or IP address) it will listen to.

The workaround is using the standalone .tar.gz package and editing manually the server.xml file.

